# SVG group types: user groups vs clip/mask carriers

Not all `<g>` elements are user-created groups. The editor must distinguish between them.

## Clip/mask carrier groups

A `<g>` is a **clip/mask carrier** if it has a `clip-path` or `mask` attribute (e.g. `<g clip-path="url(#...)">`). These are structural — the user didn't create them and shouldn't select or ungroup them as a unit.

```typescript
private isGroupAClipMaskCarrier(groupId: string): boolean {
  const el = svg.findOne(`#${groupId}`)?.node as Element | null;
  if (!el) return false;
  return el.hasAttribute('clip-path') || el.hasAttribute('mask');
}
```

## Selection behavior

- **Click on a shape inside a user group** → select the **group** (not the leaf shape).
- **Click on a shape inside a clip/mask carrier** → select the **leaf shape** directly (treat the carrier as transparent).
- **Double-click on a selected group** → drill into the group so subsequent clicks select individual children.
- Track drill-in state (e.g. `drilledIntoGroupId`) and reset it on: selection clear, undo/redo, group/ungroup.

## Layer tree

- Include `<g>` elements in the layer tree as collapsible nodes with `children`.
- Skip `<defs>`, `<clipPath>`, `<mask>`, `<title>`, `<desc>`, `<metadata>`, and `<style>` when building the layer tree.
- Use `data-name` attributes for human-readable layer names; fall back to `id` then tag name.
